tao: amian so tao? no-kakwa i-m-angay mengep so ovi?

english: the child said to his father

english: The rooster took her far away."

english: The father said, "Oh, the rooster took her!"

tao: y-amian lo chia? so tao? koan-ta
english: "Is there anyone (of our own people) here?"

tao: koan-ta no tao? ori? lo ya-makarang a-takakal

english: the child said, "Here you are, Mother!"
"You are not my child," said his mother.

tao: koan-a no anak-ne-m boken a si-ina-ko-imo koan-a

tao: maniring o anak-ne-m ni-salep-na-imo no kangkang no k-angay-ta mang-ali so ovi? sio? koan-a

tao: maniring s-ina-na-m ning koan-a noyod-ko-imo a anak-em mangwat-kamo so chinwat koan-a
english: His mother said, "If it's true you are my child, when boiling water is thrown on you
We'll see if you'll be killed."

tao: taktakana-rana o anak-na no dinwat-em tongwos
english: Boiling water was thrown on her child.

tao: maniring o ina-ne-m manoyong a anak-o-imo koan-a
english: "You're truly my child!" said his mother.

tao: mai-rana sira lo vagay-ta madiora o ina-na
english: and returned to their house accompanied by the mother.

tao: maniring o ana-ne-m mengep ta-ka-mo so vato koan-a
english: His father said, "Let's take some stones

tao: y-atei-ta so vagay-ta ta-manginanawa ta-ka-mo di-mai koan-a
english: and make the stone walls of our house, but be careful."

tao: ka-pangay-ta so aro dinalolot lo vagay-ta
english: Then they put many spirit-weapons in their house

tao: mai-rana lo kangkang-em apoapoasena? o atei-na lo vagay-ta
english: They went to the rooster's house and took stones from his house to their house.

tao: ingongona o katawtaw-ne-m m-angay-rana lo ilaod o kangkang
english: The rooster had gone to a foreign country.

tao: m-angay-ta lo takay mang-anak-o kwan-a ina-na

She went to dig for gold.
She said to the child, "Come here." The mother goes.
The child sees the spirit take the mother up to the sky.

tao: lavi a no anak-na s-ina-na k-aoli-na

english: "Where is your mother?" said his father.
"The spirit crept up and flew away with Mother."

They saw his house in the foreign country.
"You go home to your own people,"

ko-mi-chitagen no mavakes-ko naket-na no kwaway

tao: m-angay-ka lo makarang no tokon kwan-a no tao

"and see there how your wife is being cared for."
"Who are you coming here to look for your mother?

tao: nak-nakem-ko-inyo? anak no yamen lo yami

I wonder if you are really our child, dear.

tao: so pasavoren-ko dinwen no maomlesan so chinwat-an

She washed him and the child was fine, so she said, "You are really our child."
"Let's go and see them catching fish."
She made a hat, and went

english: "You are going, dear child," said his mother.

tao: m-angay-ka chyaa? no apia tao kwan
english: It doesn't matter if you do go. They are good people over there.

tao: apia non m-angay-ko-rana kwan m-angay kalilyan o vaonda
english: "Yes, good people; so I'll go," he said, and went to the plain (where the mother had been taken up).
The child cries, "You are so very tall.
I'm afraid, because I'm just little."
"I don't want to; I am not going, because Mother will scold us.

tao: y-abo m-angay-ko mwama to kongyan avay-aken ina
english: I'm not going to do planting in the mountains. Mother will scold me.
I'm going to look for something here in the trees."
"Then I'll cut off your mother's head. That's why I'm going."
"I don't want you to. I musn't let mother's head be cut off.
I'm going to cut off your mother's head."
"Yes," and the child began to cry.
After five days, he cut off her head.
and cried, "Your mother's blood is flowing down.
They went home and combed their hair
He saw the mother's spirit, and she said, "You were not bad.
My head was cut off and are you crying?
Look at me." "Let us both go,"
"Excuse me, Machinara, I'm going to sit by our betel nut basket.

tao: tao no kakwa amyan so avang to titiwen kwan-da
english: A long time ago, there was a ship at Titiwen.

tao: ma-chita-da to madegdeg (imorod no tao) / (tao d-imorod)
english: Early in the morning, the people from Imurud saw them (ship's crew).

tao: sira mi-ripo-ripos mang-aep-tamo so matengteng otwen kwan-da
english: His relatives said, "Let's take some cold food

tao: itoro-tamo-dira kwan-da m-angay-tamo lo tatala kwan-da
english: to give them, and go over in our boat."

tao: non kwan-da m-angay-sira lo tatala m-angay titiwen.
english: They went by boat to Titiwen

tao: tao no avang mamimin-sira ni-m-angay lo katyan miwalem lo rerchip
english: All the people from the ship had gone to Katyan and were resting in the cave.
The newcomers with the food pulled the boat up on the shore.
The newcomers with the food pulled the boat up on the shore.

tao: ma-chita-da no dewdew ina-kamo-pa so kanen kwan-da
english: As soon as the foreigners saw it, they said, "Give us some food."

tao: ipanchi no tao i-kongo-kamo-ya chiri-chiring no dewdew vawden namen kwan-da
english: The newcomers said, "Why are you here?" The foreigners replied, "You've come to bind us?"

tao: chiri-chiring no tao ning kwan-da nokomwanem vawden-tamo sira kwan-da
k-aep-da so talili-da no dewdew kwan-da
english: and take their clothes," the newcomers said.

tao: asa panisiringen-da kari ka-ma-kongo mo-ka-di-mi-lis-an kwan-da no tao
english: One of them was the leader. The newcomer said, "Get out! Why don't you move?"
The foreigner replied, "It doesn't make any difference whether I move or not. I won't move!"

tao: o nak-nakem no tao i-kongo na-di-mi-lis-i
english: Then they wondered, "Why doesn't he move?"

tao: ala amyan so ovay-da kwan-a no ama-da
english: "I know he has some gold," said their father.

tao: tona-pi-lis-a kari kwan-a amyan so ovay-da lo lisnen-na amori di-na-mi-lis-i
english: Giving him a shove, he said, "Get out! There is some gold under his seat and that's why he doesn't move."

tao: ma-chita-na no ama-da tonang-aep-a to ni-lisnen-a k-aep-na-rana-sya no ama-da
english: When the father saw it, he grabbed it.

tao: o panisiringen-da-m to-rana-lavi ikapaw-na ovay-da ni-aep no tao
english: The leader cried because he liked his gold that had been taken.

tao: malalayo-rana sira m-angay lo tatala emragbit

english: When we went to the foreign country

tao: ni-misa-namen lo ditanasay nimi-namen ni-mitko to vagay Darikod
english: we spent the night at Ditanasay, and we slept in Darikud's house.
The next morning, we had one bowl of food each.
When we got to the wharf
the soldiers looked at our names
one after the other, and then we disembarked.
They didn't want the man from Iranmiluk to go first.
The soldiers made him go back in a hurry.
So one of us was left over there.

tao: yaro karwan lo dewdew-em dy-aro-pa-sira a-ni-padi/machyora-rana
english: Many, many other foreigners accompanied us.

tao: makasasned namen-em nimi-namen ni-makasasned namen di-sinko
ditagen namen o araw-em ni-maligen o araw
english: Looking at the sun, we saw that it was mid-day.
We just had a little money.

tao: walem-nem/namen-a k-angay-nemn/namen-a-rana o mavang to alilo
english: We walked up to where we boarded the bus.
We gave over one hundred dollars and fifty cents over there to get here.
And so we arrived at Taytu and here
When I was getting ready to come to this country

tao: ni-myora-sira a-kano i-ra-ralay ni-mai-sira lo vagay-ko
english: accompanied by the believers, they first went to my house.
There were three of them; Siang had gone

tao: ni-mang-an-anao lo karwan no ili y-arwa
english: to teach in two other villages.
After the house had been all swept (and we had made our trip here)

tao: ipanda-ko s-ama-n-kalako so anem-a-poo a niripi o asa-ka-tao-em
english: I, Saman Kalaku, was the only one that received six hundred dollars.
"I'll take twenty dollars of the money," I said

tao: non kwan-ko yana-k-angay-rana o niripi-am ka-pito-araw kwan-ko
english: I'll go now. That was the money for seven days."

tao: a-yana-ni-pangep ni-padinga-nina? so ipiveravera so ngoso
a-kano siken a-kano vaynget a-kano alavat
english: some soap, a towel, and a bag.
So he spent one hundred dollars.

tao: inyoranayam mang-anak-o-em ano amyan so panchy-an-da-ninyo-em
english: My dear children, when the foreigner in Imurud is lecturing all of you

tao: toka-malo-malovot ano ipanchi-di-nyo no tao d-imorod a-dewdew
english: My dear children, when the foreigner in Imurud is lecturing all of you
then take some advice from an old person.
When there's much work to be done

tao: sino mapasalasala lo chir-chiring no pangangavangen
english: everybody should obey the commands of the foreigner.

tao: ano kapi-k-ali-namen lo tokon-em ato-namen ako-yakoyab-yab
english: When we're digging every afternoon on the mountain

tao: poken-em marikna-namen-pa kwan-amen a-mangday so araw akak-agep-an/ (mangday so agep)

english: Every day and every evening, you come home crying, little children.

tao: Cai Ing Won cong tong na italamozong seyvo a yanig do "Yancomin-co"
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

tao: yadoa so ikatlo a poo awan do jikang na sicarow am. nipadket do vakong a ngaran tao do kahasan am "San-Paw,"pipakatkaten ranam ablisen rana o San-Paw.kangaran da jiaten am "Yancomin,"okmarana sosan am pakaron rana akmeypakamotdeh an so Yancomin.ya manehed kamo tao do ilaod a Yancomin. sicarow am pazasagenta rana do kapiapian,kataotao da rana yaken no syevo yakomzeb so hannyaneg namen jinyo,do amranaw mahap nakapat so awawan jidamomowan ninyo ori namen kamoan ninyo kanigan ninyo Yancomin.
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

tao: ko hanoyongan ta na yatodanngay sicarow yam, yamyan so yamanci no cireng:ta ikongo a kapalogod so moin jira ori sicarow yam,ko kasnekan ninyo am ko valiaten o mapakamotdeh so onooned,ori ko kasnekan ninyo dojia.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

tao: Ji pasalita ocireng ko,o namen kamoan ninyo a tao do jiam, yamranow so nakapat do awawan no kakwa,amyan rana inyo mivaay do kalaodan.amyan so ciricireng da, kano iweywawalam da,ratateng am omrahan sira o jida nipyan no dehdeh do jia.
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

tao: tomakasi Yancomin a tao do ilaod, nipakamotdeh a nitovoyan da mivahay do kahasan, tolavi so oned sira inyapoan nyo a Yancomin,a to dabo rana so akawan nipehes da, a kamolongan da italamozong no dehdeh do ilaod. am ji dasnesnekan a pilamlamsoy no beken na manehed a tao do ilaod. do asaka sasoodan no tao picakarang yam,a mapakamotdeh so icyatatao am, marahet o vazay an,am o kabedbedan do ilaod a kagoman no aroa tao, ikongo ya patown sya so mararahet ta vazay no seyvo,ni makdeng am mamlis o seyvo so nakenakem,aapen takamo do pya so onooned,vonasen raraten do kalaod,ahap ta mango-nong do piararahan no tao,ji pasala a nakenakem,ori ko ilogodan jinyo a kasnekan kalovotan nyo a Yancomin.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

tao: "Taiwan-Tong-Seh" o vakong do ilaod,ni vatvatkan dam o saka cireng manireng am: "taiwan aboo masaod na, tao do Helan ni pangayan jia,mingaran si Cen-seh ni mapeyvazay sya,Cin-tai ni amood sya."ori nakenakem da no marahet a tao do kalaod ya.am manakem pa o nimanma na pa nimyan do ilaod a tao.beken na amyan so masaod no dehdeh sira tao. ori namen kamoan ninyo kanigan ninyo Yancomin.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: Tao do He-lan a kani Cen-cenkong panisiringen am nipehsan da sira,a pikaboaboo da sira Pinpo-Co,nipehes da jira o aakawon da.mai sira o nipong am, pilamlamsoy da Yancomin.ratateng am mai rana o kokominto ranam marahrahet pa pakamotdeh ta so Yancomin,amranow a mahap na kapat a kawan.to makarilaw sira tao do ilaod Yancomin.abo rana akawan nipehsan no mapakamotdeh a dehdeh no kanang pa. ori namen kamoan ninyo kanigan ninyo Yancomin.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: Yancomin-co do ilaod am apiya o iwawalam nyo.ni mapo ya do ineynapoa tenteneng so aapan sya.maoyat kamo mihakao do karatayan.am mai rana vazavazay no seyvo am.somazok rana Yancomin mivaay do kahasan.ta jidapia sira mihakakao do mina akawan.ni littan da kapehes da sira.torana balinas o iwawalan no Yancomin.jida nyaninigan do Yancomin. ori namen kamoan ninyo kanigan ninyo Yancomin.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: Yancomin amyan so cirecireng nyo a tao.no keyan no nipong do jiam.zavoren no nipong o cireng nyo.no ka 1945 nyan mai rana kokominto am.ipanci da yaten macinanao do cyokok.jida myan no kokominto kapizizyak so cirecireng no Yancomin.ori nikakteb na mablis o ciring nyo a Yancomin.orim namen kamoa ninyo kanigan ninyo a Yancomin.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: No kannang am,o kokominto nilitan da tao do pongso,yangay da o kosozi do irala.jida niahaes no seyvo tao do pongso.yamiyawawan o kosozi pangyan do pongso,yamkomava so kataotao no pongso ori nikeyngen no onooned no tao,aro mikayngeyngen a tao do pongso. orim ko kanigan jinyo o tao do pongso.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

tao: Pinpo-co ranam,ikongo aro dehdeh nimzagpit do avak no ilaod do kaozi nam, jida pya o Pinpo- co mizizyak so cireng da, ori nikabalinas no cirecireng da,na ikaro no Pinpo-co ji makatenengi do kataoan da a Yancomin. orim namen kamoan ninyo kanigan na Pin-poco.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

tao: mablis rana o seyvo do vazavazay do pikakatkatan am,miyan rana o kazyakan no Yancomin. padketen a kazyakan am ngaran nan: "Yancomin-co Cipen-Va."manoyong do aapan so vazavazay no Yancomin,am ikongo do jida pakpakdengi o vazavazay no seyvo ta. orim namen kamoa ninyo kanigan ninyo.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: da kazyakan o "Tow-yan won-hwa" mahap so pya iwawalam no tao.am kangay na sicarow am,jiabo na kanimablis no seyvo do rehrehten a jiamomoan a mapakamotdeh so Yancomin,o citan da do Yancomin am: abo so nezpi,abo angangayan,a jia totopos mivilang so vakong,jia kakarangan da pivatvatkan siram. orim namen kamoa ninyo kanigan ninyo.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

tao: namen jianipeyvazay o karilawan ninyo,yato dangay do katatapilan nyo.a yani ka hanhan nikagisoan do alalaw nyo. orim namen kamoa ninyo kanigan ninyo. sicaraw akmi kataotao da rana yaken no syevo yakomzeb so hannyaneg namen jinyo mamimin a Yancomin.a yanikaidan do jigang a ya nikahai am,beken na do kasaraw ni logodan,beken na asaka cireng a vatvatek do vakong an,ka to davonas rana kaboo no raraten do nimlapo ya no kakoa do seyvo ta,am sicaraw rana ahaapen takamo do piya nakem. a mabalinas kalan ta so seyvo do raraten a ka piyangangay a tao do kalaodan.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

tao: aapen ko pa o saka cireng ni mapo do Tai-yan,ikongo do "ma-noyong"icireng no Tai-yan do rarakeh am panci da "Balay" koan na.am kapya so oned do cireng dam"Sbalay."ori manoyong so piya nakem ri,a cireng no Tai- yan:Sbalay.yamikadoa ori am manoyong mapo do onooned patowa an so aapan takamo do piya vazavazay do seyvo.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

tao: do iwawalam no Yancomin am.nomyan so kalasan no tao jira,beken na asaka cireng a 〝ko ikamo imo 〞koan na.ta rarahen da o rarakeh mai amamizing so kalasan nang,mapo do oned a ikamoan no karoan tao dang. mateyka ranam minom sira so ikasaray so onooned kato da pikaboboa so ka oyan do icatatao.ori cireng no rarakeh do Tai-yan o "Sbalayo "
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

tao: inaoy sicaraw rana ipandan ta sya so rarahet a vazay jiyaten.manoyong do oned kablis so marahet a vazavazay do seyvo a Yancomin.si mateyka ko rana do jiam.amyan jinyo tovisan so cireng nyo. ka balinas so pioyaoya no marahet do onooned karahet no tao.yacita an so cireng no Tai-yan "Sbalay"do kalaod an.kabo na rana do kalovatan ta tao do ilaod a vazavazay.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

tao: Manma napa ipilovotan so nakem.beken o Yancomin kano Pinpo-co ampivazay sya. ta panirsirngeng do seyvo am pivazay syo mahap so vazay an,a beken na ipanci do ngoso ikazyak a cireng.manoyong seyso am raralay jinyo ikasnek a piyanen do oned ko sya.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

tao: o nakenakem ko sicaraw ya am,patneken ko Yancomin -Co iwawalam manoyong a pihahan na apyacireng,a kazagoman nyo a Yancomin,yaken an panisirengan do seyvo am ilovolovoten ko jinyo Yancomin. akma tamo saka onooned aapen do piya vazavazay.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

tao: makdeng pa cireng ko am nimakarang na Cong-Tong-Vo aapen do icavazay an amizezngeng alalaw nyo a Yancomin- co.macilovot dang o Pinpo-co kamimin na Yancomin,ori patoawan so cireng nyo jiaken.
english: I want to stress that this commission places the greatest importance on equality between the country and the indigenous peoples. The election of tribal representatives, including for the Pingpu ethnic group, will take as basis the consensus of peoples and tribes. This commission will serve as a mechanism for collective decision-making by indigenous peoples, and will ensure that the voices of tribe members find true expression.

tao: kapinpin na rana ori, Sin-Cen-Yan pikaigi an o makdeng pa "Yancomin-Co cipen- Va"a padketen iwawalan nyo a vayo a vazay no seyvo ta,makoyoyat pa o seyvo do rakoa vazay ya,kablisan no adan na masalit a vazay,pitalamozong nyo do masaod,nimapo do ninyapoan nipanga- nanao so pyaiwawalam,ka pikakatkat do apan so vazay kayangay an mivahay do kalaod no tao,pia kamoodan do kangangay nyo.
english: In addition, I will request that our Executive Yuan convene regularly the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law Promotion Committee, and use the Yuan's authority to coordinate and handle matters related to any consensus reached by the above-mentioned commission. These matters include the following: to retrieve historical memories, to promote indigenous self-government, to seek fair economic development, to ensure continuation of culture and education, to safeguard indigenous health, and to protect the rights of urban indigenous peoples, etc.

english: Where modern laws and indigenous traditional cultures are at odds, we will set up an Indigenous Legal Service Center with a high degree of cultural sensitivity, to reduce through institutional design the growing clashes between indigenous customs and modern laws.

english: I will ask the relevant agencies to immediately pull together cases in which indigenous community members have been indicted or sentenced for hunting, where the hunting was done in accordance with traditional customs, on traditional lands, and for non-transactional needs, and where the animals hunted were not protected by conservation laws. For such cases we will deliberate solutions.

english: I will also direct relevant agencies to present an investigative report on the decision-making process of nuclear waste storage on Orchid Island. Before finding a permanent solution for the nuclear waste, we will provide the Yami tribe appropriate compensation.

english: At the same time, under the principle of respecting the Pingpu ethnic group's self- identity, and recognizing their identity, we will examine relevant laws before September 30 of this year, so that Pingpu ethnic group identity will receive the rights and status it deserves.

english: On November 1 of this year, we will begin to delineate and announce indigenous traditional territories and lands. The system of tribal public corporation is already in place. In the future, the ideals of indigenous self-government will be realized step by step. We will step up the pace and submit for legislative deliberation three laws of great importance to indigenous peoples: the Indigenous Peoples Self-Government Law, the Indigenous Peoples Land and Sea Areas Law, and the Indigenous Languages Development Law.

english: Later this afternoon, we will convene a national indigenous peoples administrative meeting. In that meeting, the government will elaborate on the policies. On every August 1 to come, the Executive Yuan will report to the indigenous peoples our progress on restoring historical justice and transitional justice. To implement the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law, to serve indigenous historical justice, and to lay the foundation for indigenous self- government - these are the three major goals for the government's policy towards indigenous peoples.

I want to buy some clothes.

tao: yakman so ajin o mo i kaza?
english: What kind of clothes do you like?

tao: ko manazang so ainged so ari lawang.
english: I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.

tao: ya pamyan so ya malavang kano mowgaraw.
english: We have white and blue ones too.

tao: toro mo jyaken o ya mowgaraw.
english: Please give me the clothes in blue.

tao: molingwan, kani mangey jino no kacitoai ang? ka ni mangey mapazigton?
english: molingwan, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

tao: beken, ko ni mangey manazang so yakan ni yakes.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

tao: ori i, kameywalam si mahep, a pya ka peyheza ta koman.
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?

tao: taosya, ta ko mangey manazang so ayob ko.
english: No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.
Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?
The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.
How much are these sweet potatoes?

tao: yat loa poo yasa ka naneng.
i panta mo yaken so a doabedbe da yakan, kano asa ka naneng a wakey.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

tao: kanosang, ko niya ow o ipivatvatek a pya ka pa mood ko jimo?
english: kanosang, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?

tao: yabo jyaken, o yam si mangaz.
english: I don't have one either. This is mangaz's.

tao: apya ka vood kopasya, ciaha ta makeykai ko a ma paoli sya jimo.
english: Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.

tao: ayoi, i panci mo yaken a ya somarey nya ji mangaz.
english: Thank you and thank mangaz for me.

tao: ko paolien o adoa ka vakong.
english: I want to return these two books.

tao: noon, ya mya pa so mo ikakza?
english: No problem and what else do you need?

tao: ko mamood so atlo a ka vakong.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.

tao: ciana, manakem mo do i katlwarow na, ka paoli mosya.
english: Sure and remember to return them after three days.

tao: mo pa jya nitoro o ipangongopas.
english: You haven't returned me the eraser.

tao: asyo ko na jya kala o ipangongopas.
english: Then, why is my eraser missing?

tao: a la mo ni pavood ji tanakasang.
english: Maybe you lend it to tanakasang.

tao: ko jyatenngi. mange ko pala i panahes jya.
english: I don't know. If so, let me go and ask her first.
I will lend you my eraser first.

tao: pozngit, o ayob yaam nani pavood jimo ni yopan?
english: pozngit, did yopan lend you this coat?
No, my mom bought it for me.

tao: yamey yangey o ayob nyo a kani yopan.
english: yopan's coat is the same as yours.

tao: ya jimey yangey, tamavaheng o ayob na.
english: His coat is black, so our colors are different.

tao: azaon, kani mamood ji mahanang so nizpi?
english: azaon, did you borrow money from mahanang?

tao: yamyan, ko poapaolin siciarow ya am, ko jini manakem o nizpi.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?
I will return to him tomorrow.

tao: alpidan no vato o vavahey no karam a irakep sira.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay.

tao: ori i, ko jyatatenngi, ori ko ji makarakpisya.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

tao: nana o on ko imo a mapakapya so ilita do karam.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up the trap.

tao: noon! yapiya! no mangey ko am makarakep kona so o mawmalalam.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

tao: mangap ka so kekezdas, tamangey ta do orata, yamatamek rana.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

tao: ya myan do katangked no yala, si somdep ka am alilin na cita.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.
Be careful. The sickle is very sharp.

tao: ji mo todey zasagi o ko litan do omow malalam.
a ji nayanan no mo panlilitan?

english: My trap is under that tree.

tao: yamyan so koni singkad jya, ori ko ipakateneng do nayanan.
english: I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

tao: oyam ipanakep so a mong, ya pangain do oyo.
english: This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

tao: yabo jyamen o manpoy a ipangap so among, tanamen mamasil no pakow yan.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.

tao: namen pa jya ni mamasil, sipisa am nanaon mo yaken.
english: I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?
Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.

tao: no ipisaam nanaon ko imo ma pakapya so pangozongan so among.
english: I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

tao: ya mey gonagoney o pakowyan mo, vaozen mo, ta nanyakan no among.
english: Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

tao: sitai, tayameygona goney avang, tokong yan jya am ngingit sya.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

tao: a pen mo jya, ta sidongen ko imo am lolo sya.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

tao: yatey ya pyasicirow ya, ni mapno o karey ta no among.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.
Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.

tao: jikamna mialilima, lisna kamna do ezsadan.
english: Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

tao: sinci 5 sicyaraw, ya miwalam simaraw, miyowyaw ta an!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!

tao: noon! mangay ta do pais no ayo.
english: Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

tao: sinci 3 simaraw, mibozo ta simakoyab an!
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!

tao: ikongo vazay mo do pepnezak simaraw?
english: What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

tao: niciyo simaraw, yamen mi-ina am, yamangay do kyokay.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.

tao: ko akmi ya mowtowta, ko mangay do o bowbotan.
english: I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

tao: sinsi, ya meyngen velek ko, mangay do o bowbotan.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?

tao: yana makaykai rana miwalam, citai na am mangay ka.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

tao: sinsi, ya meyngen oo ko, miwala ko simakoyab.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

tao: noon, makapiya ka mowli do vahay nyo.
english: Okay, take care and go home.

tao: sinsi, miwalam ko simaktey sinci 1, ko mangay do koysang.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

tao: ya meyngen velek na, ya amyan do obowbotan.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

tao: sinsi, yameyngen tetehnan na niKaswal, ya miwalam sicaraw.
english: Teacher, Kaswal has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

tao: ngaran ko, Si.NGazamo, sicyawan am, ko asangernan so kakawakawan.
english: My name is Si.NGazamo, and I'm 10 years old.

tao: anak do ajin a yancominco imo?
english: What ethnic group are you from?

tao: anak no tao do pongso ko.
kanyo madadaya saka vahay ya yancomin?
english: Are all your family members indigenous?
Yes, my whole family is Yami.

tao: beken, tao do pongso si.yama, dehdeh si ina.
english: No, my father is Yami, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

tao: syama mo ito? yana apira kakawakawan na?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

tao: syamamo ito? yana pira o kakawakawan na?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

tao: beken, iyam rarakeh do ili namen, yana waongernan so kakawakawan na.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

tao: yana apira kakawakawan nikakamo a meakay?
yana awoa so ikarwangernan o kakawakawan ni kaka a meakay.
ya rako wawang no kakawakawan na jimo nikaka mo a meakay?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

tao: ko apata angernan asa poo so kakarakarang.
tana mownay jini misinkad, kakmi ya nimipakarang?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

tao: nonan, kona atlo a ngernan asapoo so kakarakarang.
noon, ya atlo angernan ko karehrehmet.
ko kalaen sinsi do da pivazayan.
english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

tao: ya amyan do mibebneng a pilwawatan, citaina am ya minenenet a milwawat.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

tao: ajin na yanan niMatnaw? citaina am ya minenenet a malalayo.
english: Where is Matnaw? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

tao: ya amyan do panaralayan dang, mangay ko ipanci siya.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

tao: mangay ko pa manazang so kanen do mararaw, citaina am kalaen ko imo.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

tao: pikala so tao, ko kalaen sinsi.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

tao: Maomay yami nenenet manpokpok sicyaaw so bozo?
english: Is Maomay competing in croquet today?
No, he's competing in high jump.
Will you compete in the sports day?
What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.

tao: simiwondokay am mipanazang tamo so kanekanen?
english: Will we sell food at the sports day?

tao: jabo, namen mipanazang so avyoten a bozo.
kani makahap so icibang, ka teywaraya!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!

tao: ya amyan syakes ta do vahay?

english: Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

tao: jyabo, na kapa kowbot pa, simaep am nayai.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

tao: ya amyan syakay ta do vahay?
ya amyan do mivava a kadoa no vahay, angaz am kala sya.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

tao: Kaswal? yana mownay jini macita imo, ka papiya?
english: It's Kaswal. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?
I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

tao: ya amyan do panonotongan mapasisit so yasay, panci ko siya an?
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.
She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

tao: jiabo akay nyo do vahay, ya amyan do akaon, amyan kanyo do vahay mapa nanala siya, an?
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

tao: ya mownay jini macita, ka nimipakarang.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.
It's so good to see you.

tao: o pinapo ya am, ya itoro jinyo, pangay nio do pangarerekmehan.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

tao: ka na mownay jinimai, ko ipanci inyo ya koman.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

tao: jimoa rawtan, to kona ngiyop so cinwat, mangay tamo dosdepan miwalam.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.

tao: ayoy nakem mo jyaken, ko na mangay.
english: Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

tao: apen mo paya o manok an, yabo ko itoro jimo.
english: Here's a chicken for you, just a little something.

tao: simaraw do makoyab am misinmota an?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

tao: mangayta do pivatvatkan an? namen miloin.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

tao: a mangay do kadponponan tao a vahay, a mivinavinayoan ko so mibintebtekan.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

tao: yapiya citaen do ili namen vonitan a misavong, simisavong rana am, kalaen mo yaken!
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

tao: simangay rana do amyan sawnam, teymownay rana.
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Harvest Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

tao: ko ipaci jimo am, mo ipivahay do ili.
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.

tao: a mo jingyani do karowan tao a mapivatvatek?
english: Why not teach in the city?

tao: noon ta ko ikapaw o pongso namen, inaoy ta masidong ko o ili namen.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

tao: ka mateneng tominon, sino ninanao imo?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

tao: siyakes, iya am, nimateneng na tominon do ili namen.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.

tao: mo pakanakem a ya macinanao do tominon?
english: How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

tao: iwawalam namen o cininon ya, ko kakdain iwawalam namen am loslos do malavayo.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

tao: ya maganinam yopen o nipareng a saki.
ka teywara ya, mownay pansahadan ya?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

tao: ala kapito araw kapiyana rana. panmaen mokis kano kadai dendengen kapangay so odong a kocikoten, kapiyana rana pakozongen do vanga.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

tao: ya amyan ja so tonggazasi kano yasay, madadaya nimoa ko!
english: I have chili and chinese cabbage, both grown by myself!

tao: no adoa sazangan am, apira nginana?
alima ngernan kadoana ranaw no nizpi.
ko ikakza o ayob ya, apira ngernan?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

tao: teymasingat rana, maraet kapapereh pa sya?
english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?

tao: maraet, sipaepepen am, ji ko makanizpi.
english: No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

tao: noon na! mangap ko so saka masirema ayob.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

tao: apen ko ipangan ya, kano kama ya.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

tao: mamimin adoa zivo, madadaya niparpareng ko ya, ji moaraetan karaetna.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

tao: sipanci kagagan ko manazang am, paperen mo nizpi?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

tao: noon! cyata paperen ko nizpi na.
english: Alright! I will give you a discount.

tao: aikanyo jya! ya amyan so ayob kano sakop ya ipanazang.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

tao: saka ayob am, alima ngernan katlona ranaw, no atlo am asa zivo.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

tao: asa sazangan ko, toro jaken vayo.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

tao: akokay, ko kakdain manazang so nidengdeng a kadai a kano nimay
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and Taro cake with maqaw pepper.

tao: yabo rana o kanen. ya amyan pa o taroy, sazangan mo?
english: The rice is sold out. I have bacon, would you like to buy some?

tao: noon! toro asa jyaken, sipisa am manazang ko so kanen.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

tao: noon, pakozongen ko do alavat, o ya am alima poo a ngernan.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

tao: ya na ikapito no toki am ko mangay do gako.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

tao: ya mapakzikzing am, ya somdep do pivatvatekan o sinsi namen, maniring o nipamnekan namen a panirsiringen am "tomanek! amlogod."
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

tao: "kamina kong" koan namen a ya mazizigton.
macinanao namen am, nanaoen na yamen no sinsi do ipivilavilang no Tao.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Yami language of numbers.

tao: namen to macilolo do sinsi a mivilang, namen nianood paa o anood no vilavilang.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

tao: ya aro o ko katengengan rana ciriciring no Tao.
english: I have learned many Yami languages.

tao: ko mangday so araraw a mangay do gako, ko mangday so araraw a macinanao do ciriciring no Tao, ta ipamizing ko jira ama a ka ni ina.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Yami language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

tao: ngaran ni ama am siaman Manineng.
ngaran ni ina am sinan Manineng.
ya asa ngarnan o kakawakawan ko siciawan ya.
ya asa o kaka ko a mehakay, ngaran na am si Manineng, ya asa so ikaroa na ngarnan no kakawakawan na.
english: I have a brother, his name is Manineng, he is 11 years old.

tao: ya namen miyangay so pivatvatekan a gako.
english: We study in the same school.

tao: yaken a ka ni kaka mehakay am, namen teymakey a mianoanood.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

tao: ko makey a miawawat, no ya miwalam am, namen mangay miawawat a asa ka vahay.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

tao: ko makey a maciboang do vayo a kagagan, ta apia a kapieza namen a mangay mianoanood a ka no miawawat.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.

tao: yaken am anak no tao do pongso.
namen lalima a ka tao do vaay namen.
english: There are five people in our family.

tao: namen talo a maketeketeh do vaay namen.
english: There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

tao: yaken a ka ni ama a ka ni ina a ka nira kaka a ya matovong do vaay namen.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

tao: ya makarang si ama, si ama am mikalsong.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

tao: Ya magolang si ina, si ina am koysang.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

tao: No ya mian si ama do vaay namen am, na sirisiringen yamen no ciring no tao do pongso.
english: My father speaks the Tao language with us at home.

tao: namen makarakarala do pongso no ya maid o araraw no namen ipiweywalam.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

tao: Yaken a ka nira kaka am namen mateneng a manozatoza.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

tao: Ko isaray yamen a asa ka vaay.
english: I like our family very much.

tao: no ka madagdag ya am namen niamlivon si ina.
english: I went out with my mother today.

tao: ya mowgaraw o angit no ya maraw, o kakawan am ya ji arekmeh a ya ji annget, a ya masazowsaw.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

tao: namen mian do Jipanatosan am, namen kanen o mavaw namen, o zezak am ya tomiray do kataotao namen a ya ikehteng.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.

tao: ya makoyab am, ya mipabazangbang rana o angit.
english: In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

tao: ko pacicin si ina am, "ya na ikabazangbang no angit ang?"
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

tao: maniring si ina am "ala ya amian so pagpag a ya mai."
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

tao: ya mahep rana am abo rana o cinalab do angit, ya mitotoaw rana o mata no angit.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

tao: ya namen mangay rana do vahay namen.
namen mian pa do rarahan am, ko patanangen o nakenakem ko do mata no angit.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

tao: inaoy no ji ngai o kakawan, ta ko akzeben pa a kalivon.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

tao: ya mian do katangked no vahay namen o gako ko, ko mangday so araraw a ya malam a mangey do gako, no ya misiasiay am ko malam a moli do vahay namen.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

tao: ya alikey o gako namen, ya abo do na ka aro no ya mivatvatek a kakanakan, so namen ipakasingkad do kadoan jiamen.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

tao: namen maloalovot do rako a inaorod no gako namen a ya mibozo a ya mawalawalam.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

tao: sia mai a macialalam jiamen o sinsi, namen akmey a asa ka vahay a ya mian do gako.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

tao: namen mangday so araraw do gako a ya mivias, ta namen pingsanan o saad no namen pacinanaoan a vahay.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

tao: tatasa ka tao am ya omlinas do pazezevengan, karoan jiamen am ya mivias.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

tao: mangay do sirisiri no gako namen a ya namen avyasan, namen tominanakman o maciavazavazay namen a ya pivazain, so na kawadwad no gako namen a mangday so araraw.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

tao: nokakyab am, nimangay ko a ataoen si akay do Jimowrod.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

tao: ko mownay rana ji nimacita si akay, ko ikapaw iya.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

tao: na ka pakacita jiaken ni akay am, na pakanen yaken so somon, na ka pinom jiaken so asoy no anioy.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink coconut juice.

tao: ya maganinam o na nimoa ni akay a somon, ya teyapia kanen.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

tao: ko ikakey o asoy no anioy, ta ya manao a inomen.
english: I also like coconut juice, it's tasted good too.

tao: ya miigen o araw am, ko sidongen si akes a ya manotong.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

tao: ya aro o na nipansahadan ni akes a iyakan namen, ya mian so among a ka no manok a ka no piniow a ka no peyret.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and river snails.

tao: namen teyka koman am, namen mangay mangotod so voong no balangbang.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

tao: ya aro o wakay a ka no soli a ka no vizaoz a da nivaon jiaken nira akay.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and melon, and asked me to take them home.

tao: ko taitaiden rana sira akay am, ko maniring am "sira akay kong, akes kong, cia'a ta sipisa am mai ko a omatao jinio an."
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

tao: nokapepnezak am, na yangay yamen no sinsi do panitanitan so omalalam, namen mian do asdesdepan am ya namen minazabi a manazang so kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

tao: namen somdep rana do panitanitan so omalalam am, maniring o sinsi am "ya mian do kananman tamo eya am miasasalap, do teyrala rana ori am volavolay, to tanio ngonongi o kapilingalingay takamo."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

tao: ko mamogaw no volay ang, so ji ko nimangai do dang a manita.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

tao: aro o nimacita ko a miasasalap, somalasalap sira do toos, macita ko pa a o totoo a mitkeh do tonga no kayo.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

tao: karoan no omalalam am mian so panganpen a ka no baka a ka no kokoman so tao, ji ko pa nimakacita so akman so sang a omalalam, ko macita rana siciaraw ya am ko na masaray.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

tao: ya aro o ko nisiva a siasing, ta ko ipacita jira ama a ka ni ina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

tao: sipisa am macizeza ko jira ama a ka ni ina a mai do jia.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

tao: no kapiwalam ya am, nimangay namen si kaka a mavakes do Taitong a omatao si maran.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

tao: nimapo namen do pongso a omavang do sikoki a mangay do Taitong.
english: We took the train from Lanyu to Taitung.

tao: makaranes namen do Taitong am, mialeleh si maran a tomazapia jiamen do sinanap.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

tao: o vahay ni maran am abo do karai na do sinanap, so nikakeykai na makaranes.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

tao: do katangked no vahay ni maran am mian so rako a pamangamanganan so baka, ori nikalololo namen a mialeleh a mangay do dang.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

tao: mian namen do pamangamanganan so baka am, pehzaen na yamen ni maran a mapamangan so kagling a ka avang namen do likod no baka.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

tao: maep rana am, mehzehza namen a mangay do akakanan a koman.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

tao: aro o aleleh do avak no ili Jitaitong, so nipiotobay namen a mangay do dang.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

tao: meylis namen rana do dang am, aspangan namen o otobay a nitakaw da rana, so to namen rana ngavangi do avavangan no tao a aleleh.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

tao: siciaikoa ya am namen rana nimakarala, manngo paro o otobay ni maran a ya na rana nimakala an?
english: Now that we are back in Lanyu, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

tao: no kalialikey ko pa am mivahay namen do Jivalino, mivatvaket ko rana am mangay namen do ilaod, ori to namen ngiyani do rako a mahataw.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Jivalino. After I started school, we moved to Taiwan and have been living in the city ever since.

tao: mivatvatek ko rana do kakarangan a gako am, vilangan ko o monganay do kasasaodan no vazavazay no Yancoming a vakong, ori nipakatenngan ko rana do meyciamadadayan a iweywawalam no Yancoming do Taiwan.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

tao: ori, no ka teyteyka ya do nipiwalam namen am, yaken a ka ni kaka mehakay am nimakarala namen a omatao so apapnan namen a rararakeh, naknakmen namen kapakamizing so iweywawalam namen a Tao nokakoa.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

tao: ya sikawao so kakawakawan rana o rarakeh, am no ya citaen am akman so malavayo pa a tao.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

tao: apiaen na yaken ni akay a mapacici sia am, ipanci na o mabnek na ciriciring no peyciamahatawan. teymasonong o ipanci na ciriciring no tao, mangay do ciriciring no Ipong a ka no Amis a ka no ciriciring no dehdeh o katenngan na a ipanci.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Tao and he can even speak Japanese, simple Pangcah and Chinese.

tao: nipacici ko o rarakeh ori ipakateneng ko jia no kalialikey na pa am ninanao da no ciriciring no Ipong. no kalavayo na am nimasaneb a mangay do Taitong a manlangi do mogis no Amis, ori nipaciboang na. o ciriciring rana no dehdeh am, na nimahap do aro a kagagan na dehdeh, ori na ikaro no na katenengan a ipanci a ciriciring ang.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child.When he was young, he often went to Taitung to help the Amis harvest rice and work, and learned the Amis language; and he has many Han friends, so he can speak so many languages.

tao: no kapacici namen jira am, aro o malavat da monganay do makeyneynaapan a tao nokakoa a nitaid da a adan a teneteneng da.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

tao: tana namen ji a mimin a masilo no ciciloan a amizingen o da ipanci am, ciaha ta namen nipatoong do patowtowngan so ciriciring rana, apia no amizingen am to iwanga.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

tao: no kalialikey ko pa am ji ko pa atenngi o meyciamadadayan a masaod no iweywawala namen, ori o ikasnek ko a ipanci da a Yancoming.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

tao: ya to miparo o ya ko nimamizing am, ya ko rana katenngan o monganay do iweywawalam namen do pongso, ya mapeyzokab a ya ko pacikazwayan.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Tao is unique and something to be proud of.

tao: simakoyab ya am, ya mai rana si wari a mehakay.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

tao: namen mangay si akes do pananazangan so manok, ta dengdengen namen a yakan ni wari a mehakay.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

tao: miavas namen do pananazangan so yasay am, aro do dang o vayo pa nikotod da yasay.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

tao: kapanazang namen rana so insay a ka no ovi a ka no omaom.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and Bird's-nest fern.

tao: maniring do katangked na o pananazang so asi no kayokayo am "ya maganinam o pinapo a ka no kolitan ya, manazang kamo an!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and mango are very sweet. Buy some!"

tao: miratateng am manazang namen so pinapo a ka no kolitan.
miavas namen do pananazangan so viniay am, maniring o lawpan "ikongo o ya mo sazangan? o manok siciaraw ya am, ya arako a ya matava paa, ngina no asa am ya atlo a ranaw."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

tao: singaten ni akes kapacici na so lawpan, a apia kapaveveh so ngina na.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

tao: am maniring o lawpan am "ya ji aveveh rana o ngina na, marahet kapakas paa so ngina na."
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

tao: mian do katangked na asa ka lawpan am "manazang kamo so among ko an, ta ya ararako a ya maveveh paa so ngina."
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

tao: miratateng am manazang namen rana so manok a ka no among, mian do vahay namen am makapia namen a nimansahad do asa ka akakanan a iyakan.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.

tao: nimownay namen a to nanala si wari, todaji ahep rana.
english: After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

tao: mizingwa si wari jiamen am "ya tongian so makdeng a vazay do itaysang jia, so namen ji miwalami rana, si pisa ka piwalam am ori ko ipiwalam."
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

tao: maniring si akes am "aro a ya nidengdeng ito a, angay panci sira maran mo a maci'angang jiaten."
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

tao: ka panci namen paa nira zipos namen, mai a maci'angang jiamen.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

tao: amian kehakay ko a mingaran si Kacivaw, iya rana am mawawaden.
english: I have a classmate named Kacivaw, he often forgets to bring things.

tao: no mivatvatek namen am, mamood do kararay namen so ipivatvatek a ka no ipangongopas nojia pivatvatkan a vakong.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

tao: toda ipisa a ipidoa a ipitlo am, vooden namen pa jia.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

tao: am mian so marahet a iyangay na, o nivood na am ji na paolia rana.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

tao: am, amian so karahetan na, ta o nivood na am ji na rana paolia.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

tao: ipisa do araraw, malovot namen a mangay miyowyow.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

tao: mian pa do avak no rarahan am, kadasan si Kacivaw ori a am ji nimapalolo so ipilinalinas na mehma vakong.
english: On the way, Kacivaw wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

tao: mamood do kararay namen so ipilinalinas na am, patovisan da am "ko ji nimapalilio."
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

tao: to rana lavi si Kacivaw a mioyaoya manci no "nio rana ji voodji nia jiaken so ipilinalinas?"
english: Kacivaw burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

tao: tovisan da no kararay namen am "mo kangay ori a ya ji mapalolo, no ya vooden jimo am, mo na ji paolia!"
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

tao: ikadoa na araw am, nimadagdag si Kacivaw a makaranes do gako, ka paoli na rana so niveyvood na do kararay namen.
english: The next day at school, Kacivaw arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

tao: koan ni Kacivaw am "ji kamo makasnek ang, ciaha ta manaken ko rana o kapalolo ko so aaapen ko. ayoy o niveyvood nio jiaken a meyciamadadayan, ayoy."
english: Kacivaw apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

tao: ya makeyneynaaapan si maran do ili namen.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

tao: no kalialikey ko pa am, no makoyab am mayai do vahay namen si maran a somivah si ama, apen da o paltog a ka no zingki a miyowyaw.
english: When I was young, my uncle used to come home at night to ask Dad out. They went out with a fish gun and a flashlight

tao: no avak no ahep am, ioli da o niaaapa da do vahay namen.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

tao: nomakatakaw am vaoyo o nipaltogan da, nomakatakaw am pai nojia koyta o nisowan da, no to da sapa am anos.
english: Sometimes it was tuna, sometimes lobster and octopus, and occasionally squid.

tao: no maraw am mida ipanci sira zipos namen a mai do vahay namen a maci'angang.
english: During the day, they would invite relatives and friends to come to their homes and share the prey with their people.

tao: no macita ko si maran a mai do vahay namen am, pasaozen ko si ama a mapehza jiaken a mangday mipaltog.
english: Every time I saw my uncle coming to my house, I would quarrel with my father and take me with me to go fishing.

tao: no maniring si ama am "ji topanomanoma o ciring ta makaniow." no makaveyvow ko rana am ori ipaciboang ko.
sira memehakay do ili namen am, maloalovot sira mitawaz do awa ipiyakan so vayo a among no asa kaili.
english: The men of the tribe also go out to sea to net fish, so that the whole tribe has fish to eat.

tao: ya mateneng si ama a mamaring so paltog do awa, si maran a wari ni ama am, ya manineng a mipaltog do kalilian, ori da kasanib a meyeyheza mangahahap.
english: My dad is very good at making Harpoon. My uncle, my father's younger brother, is fishing very accurate, so they often go fishing together.

tao: to ko akzeba ka pakaveyvow ko rana a maciangay jira mipaltog, ori ikasanib ko a omtahataha a tomezgek do kalilian, ji nimeyyahahay a kapakanet na rana no ineynawa ko a somwat so kono do kalilian.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I often practiced swimming and diving, and soon my lung capacity was ready to dig for shellfish in the rocks of the sea.

tao: macita na ni ama am payaiten na yaken, no mavyay o tao am ipamaring ko imo so paltog mo an.
english: My father encouraged me when he saw it. Told me when I grow up, he would make me a shotgun.

tao: ya ko rana makaveyvow am, ya mian rana so paltog ko a maciheza jira ama a ka ni maran a mangay mipaltog.
english: Now that I'm older, I've got a fish gun and a chance to go fishing with my father and uncle.

tao: no mang-id namen rana a nimakamong am, magaga si ina a ka nira akay.
english: When we got home from fishing, Mom and Grandpa were very happy.

tao: sira akay a ka ni akes am ipanlanlag da yaken, isaray do tao do to a niomzat jiamen do kalilian a manta ni yamen so sinaaapan.
english: My grandparents will also bless me, and thank the gods for blessing us to shoot fish in the sea, give us a lot of prey.

tao: no ka madagdag am. ji ko nimapis kangay ko meyvatvatek.
english: I was late for school this morning.

tao: mangay ko do gako am, nyawaw ko a ji nimapalolo so kabang.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.

tao: ji abo nyahap ko a nipalolo.
english: I didn't bring anything with me.

tao: no kapivatvatek namen, to namen raroa a citan o asa ka vakong.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

tao: no kapisikin, voodan ko o pivatvatek aka no ipangongopas do kararay ko.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

tao: koan na yaken no sinsi, "ma dagdag ka mivangon, ji ka mipahahay!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

tao: kagagan ko si Anopan, kanakan iya do pongso.
english: My good friend's name is Anopan, and he is also an Tao child.

tao: nimiheza namen do jiratay a mivatvatek.
english: We study together in the jiratay tribe.

tao: namen masanib a amizeng so kavavatanen no rarakeh, namen matotopos manci so cireng no tao.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Tao proficiently.

tao: ko makarang a matava paa, am si Anopan yamahehep a yamagozang.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Anopan is short and thin.

tao: ya mazigton si Anopan, a da ikakza iya.
english: Anopan is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

tao: ya mipeypalalayo do peyvatvatkan sicyaraw eya, aro o nipangay a pinenenetan ri.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

tao: miyan dang so pinenenetan a kolili aka no mapatoktok so bozo aka no mipalalayo sira kano mapaltog pa.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

tao: no ka palalayo ko, ni malektek ko a ka tona piraralan no atod ko.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

tao: am mivagon ko rana a tomanek a mangay do palayyoan ko.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

tao: miyan ko rana makaranes do palayyoan ko, masasaray sira tao.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

tao: tana ji nimangay do manma na do palayyoan ko, am ko masaray, ta nimavos rana do peynenenetan ko.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

tao: yakan kani ama nimangay namen itazogaw si maran nokakyab.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

tao: nimizahza o ai na ni maran.
koan na yamen, nimakava o atep no vahay na kangyan no tong.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

tao: no kapivazay na do atep no vahay am, nimakas do atep a mizahza..
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

tao: nimapalolo si ama so asisi no baka aka no mamahen a itoro na ji maran
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

tao: ko macisirisiring ji maran do irirayan, aro na ni ononongan a vazavazay.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

tao: ko na itaytaydan si maran am, na azwazwain yaken ka namakarang a apiya so ka mawmawgan""
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

tao: koan ko am: si apiya rana o ai mo maran am. mai ka do vahay namen.
english: I said, When your foot gets better

tao: 2022 no kawan, pikaygi da abnekan no seyvo o ngaran do mibonsyow no yancomin.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

tao: pacicihen ko masanib a mazyak no vazay a abneken o mibonsyo no yancomin si Tahaw tao do pangso.
english: I interviewed si Tahaw, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

tao: yaken kani ya misirisiring namen a si niciyo ranam mangay ko do vahay da a pacicien.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

tao: pacicinen ko na do vahay da ka panci na jiaken so nikapwan no ngaran na, a ka pitotwaw da saka vahay ipakasingkad ko jira saka vahay kano sira sakayli.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

tao: pacicien ko ikongo o mo kazyakan nya do paliten o ngaran no yancomin. marahet o adan a ipadket so ngaran?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

tao: koan na yaken ni Tahaw, ta manoyong o pipipangayan no ngaran do cyokok, aro sira manci nyaken A-na, ikaro a malas a mapaming dang.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \A-na

tao: koan na ni Tahaw am, "vatvatkan no yancomin a manoyong a ngaran namen do tao. ikasawop namen malayma tao do pongso, mapo ya do nyapowan namen, ngaran namen do pongso a makdeng ya, inaoy no aroa tao mababnek so ngaran do tao a yancomin."
english: si Tahaw said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

tao: no kakyab am yakena kani akes a nimangay do pananazangan a mananazang so iyakan, aro nipalolo na ni akes o insay a nimowmowa na. kapamareng na sya so maganinam a iyakan no yancomin.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

tao: da teykaza no tao o pananazangan ni akes, aro o nisazangan da o voong no wakay aka no omaom, tahaman no aro a tao o nirotongan ni akes ri.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the Sweet potato leaves and bird's nest fern, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

tao: o nipasisit na o omaom aka no nyamay na nimay ni akes am teymaganinam ri. aka no nitazaban na taroy ya, teyapiya kakanan na ori ikaroo no manazang sya, ya miyatoatonton sira do pananazangan ni akes.
english: The bird's nest fern and Taro cake she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

tao: no yamapasisit si akes am, ko manalanala so manazang a tao. ko macyak a ipaci no, "nimownowa namen ya, teyapya ya a aboo kosozi jia, key! mai kamo manazang ang."
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

tao: ya nimakaykai na kabo rana no iyakan a nipanazang, koan na ni akes: mina imo ri a nisomidong jiaken.
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

tao: makoan rana so pananazangan a vazay, aro nipacinanaoan ko so voovoong kano iyakan no yancomin a ko katenngan sira, aka no katopsan ko o kagiso no mananazang
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

tao: macita ko si akes a makza no iyakan ta do pongso, isaray ko a ikazway do onowned ko.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

tao: asa o ikasikatlo na a ngernan
adoa o ikasikatlo na a ngernan
atlo o ikasikatlo na a ngernan
apat o ikasikatlo na a ngernan
alima o ikasikatlo na a ngernan
asa o ikasikapat na a ngernan

english: the thing stuck between the teeth
at the foot of the mountain
peeling the bark of a tree
calling (e.g. calling before feeding the chickens)
dry (e.g., drying clothes in the sun)
pack up (imperatives, as in pack up)
lift off (as in lift off the lid).
burn (as in burning the hair of prey)
marry to a non-ethnic clan member
fragile (e.g. this wire is prone to breakage)
in the process of (doing something or happening)
